<paragraph blockId="29.[160,1156,911,1076]" box="[160,409,911,937]" pageId="29" pageNumber="294">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[160,409,911,937]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="294">External morphology</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="29.[160,1156,911,1076]" pageId="29" pageNumber="294">Body elongate, thick, background colour light green with small brown and white dots along body, and a white pigmented area between eyes. Cerata numerous, flat; transparent with green lines running towards apex. Rhinophores long, folded, divided in ‘Y’ shape, tips divided into two unequal parts.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="29" pageNumber="294" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="29.[160,1155,1127,1257]" box="[160,252,1127,1153]" pageId="29" pageNumber="294">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[160,252,1127,1153]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="294">Ecology</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="29.[160,1155,1127,1257]" pageId="29" pageNumber="294">
Specimens found at night and during the day on the green algae 
<taxonomicName authority="(De Notaris, 1844)" baseAuthorityName="De Notaris" baseAuthorityYear="1844" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Caryophyllaceae" genus="Bryopsis" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="29" pageNumber="294" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="duplex">
<emphasis box="[936,1106,1163,1188]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="294">Bryopsis duplex</emphasis>
(De Notaris, 1844)
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Kutzing" authorityYear="1843" baseAuthorityName="Roth" box="[369,594,1198,1223]" class="Ulvophyceae" family="Cladophoraceae" genus="Cladophora" kingdom="Plantae" order="Cladophorales" pageId="29" pageNumber="294" phylum="Chlorophyta" rank="species" species="prolifera">
<emphasis box="[369,594,1198,1223]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="294">Cladophora prolifera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
laying egg masses. At night slugs actively crawled and laid egg masses, while by day they hid among the algae.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
